 examining negotiations of racial and ethnic identities as central to the history of religious environmentalism, this work complicates assumptions that religious environmentalism is a direct expression of theology, ethics, or religious beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmentalismxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aEnvironmentalismxReligious aspectsvCase studies. 0aEnvironmentalismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aamerica.  aamerican issues.  aamerican.  achristian.  achristianity.  aclassism.  aelite.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  aenvironmentalist.  aethics.  aethnic identity.  aethnicity.  ago green.  agreen divide.  agreen planet.  agreen religion.  agreen.  amodern world.  arace.  aracial identity.  areligion.  areligious beliefs.  areligious environmentalism.  areligious leaders.  aresearch.  ascholarship.  asocial class.  atheology.  atwenty first century.  aunited states.  aurban.  awhite elite.  awhite.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029116440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965003?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965003/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY